lter company was established in  along the codorus creek some ten miles north of the pennsylvaniamaryland border to the west of the town were the blue ridge mountains and to the east beyond the larger town of york flowed the wide susquehanna river the town’s original name spring forge reflected its early industry an iron forge which during the american revolution manufactured supplies for the continental army the forge was in operation until  when jacob hauer bought the buildings and converted them into a paper mill some  miles southeast near the maryland town of gunpowder falls another paper mill called loucks hoffman  company began operations in the s it was here in  that yearold philip h glatfelter began his first job in the paper trade glatfelter—whose wife amanda was the sister of jacob loucks—worked in the firm for seven years and in  at the height of the american civil war glatfelter decided to go into business on his own by this time hauer had died and his spring paper mill was being sold at an orphan’s probate court a printed announcement of the sale mentioned a “tract of land containing about  acres … a large stone paper mill a frame machine house stone stock house and four tenant houses” the mill itself had two burnham water wheels propelled by the codorus creek four largecapacity engines and a inch cylinder paper machine glatfelter learned about the mill from loucks whose second wife mary was the daughter of jacob hauer on december  —one month after president lincoln’s famous speech at nearby gettysberg—glatfelter bought the property for  glatfelter’s new paper business initially called spring forge mill began operations in july of  with a daily capacity of  pounds its first product was newsprint which glatfelter made from a pulp of rye straw mixed with a smaller amount of straw and rags collected from various cotton gins along the region’s railway lines this pulp material was retrieved in spacious railcars known as barns because at the time spring forge itself did not have a railway line “barns” returning from the cotton gins could get no closer than jefferson and york some five and ten miles respectively from the mill when the town changed its name in  to spring grove the company thus became the spring grove mill for the first  years newsprint continued to be the company’s main product and during this period it made impressive gains in production from the initial capacity of  pounds per day the mill was able to expand to  pounds in   in  and  by  this increased capacity was made possible by the company’s investment in new modern facilities in  for example the mill was moved farther north along the codorus creek and next to it the company constructed a new building costing  and containing an inch paper machine two years later spring forge celebrated the opening of its rail line which ran through the mill’s new site in  glatfelter entered into an agreement with pusey and jones company of delaware to build a inch fourdrinier machine allowing the mill to produce a considerably wider roll of paper named after henry and sealy fourdrinier who patented an early form of the machine in england in  the fourdrinier machine fed pulp onto a continuous wire belt shook it to remove excess water and then pressed and dried the pulp into paper glatfelter’s new fourdrinier machine was until  the largest in the world and the extremely wide paper rolls made by the machine helped him gain new customers in  when the philadelphia public ledger began operating two inch printing presses spring grove mill was the only business in the country that could supply the paper the mill also produced paper for a variety of other newspapers in pennsylvania and maryland including the philadelphia evening telegraph soon glatfelter also changed his pulpmaking methods which would result in a better quality paper prior to  the mill mechanically separated the fibers of the raw materials probably with the use of a grinder this process acceptable for newsprint and other paper intended for temporary use had a number of drawbacks mechanical separation tended to fragment and shorten the fibers thus lessening their ability to bind and make strong paper moreover fragmentation left considerable debris in the pulp and various remaining chemical constituents caused the paper to grow yellow with age even when new such paper did not have a “high whiteness” and was difficult to bleach as a result glatfelter began to take note of a new chemical method called the soda process which enabled a highquality paper to be made from wood fibers it was developed in  by englishman hugh burgess who a few years later immigrated to the united states to set up a paper mill in pennsylvania in the soda process wood chips were boiled in a caustic alkali at a high temperature and pressure afterward the separated fibers were washed in water and then bleached in  glatfelter built a giant sodaprocess mill which was used to make pulp from jack pine poplar wood and straw straw however came to be used in decreasing quantities by  this new production helped the company surpass  in total sales and four years later the number of employees reached  with its new pulpprocessing method the company in  was able to make one of its most important changes—the suspension of newsprint production and the subsequent focus on highquality paper for books lithographs and business forms for this purpose another sodaprocess pulp mill was installed in  and by the turn of the century the company had become an industry leader of highquality uncoated printing paper the founder’s son william l glatfelter entered the business in  after graduating from gettysburg college and that year he began a long apprenticeship under the guidance of his father he had already worked at the mill for  years when in  the business was incorporated as p h glatfelter company the following year the founder died and the reins to the company were handed to his son president of the company from  to  william glatfelter oversaw a tremendous increase in production as well as continued advances in chemically processed wood pulp in  in order to manage the mill’s growing need for wood he established glatfelter wood pulp company a wholly owned subsidiary with more than  acres of timberland in southern maryland additional timberland in maryland and eastern virginia would eventually boost the acreage to  william glatfelter was responsible for instituting a number of other major projects many of which were completed in the early s a new basin for storing up to  tons of coal—the fuel used to fire the company’s highpressured boilers—was constructed during this period as was a large indoor loading room where newly manufactured paper was placed on waiting railroad cars a tachometer which measured rotational speed was attached to all of the company’s machines thus providing a more accurate way to monitor production most spectacular was the new fourdrinier paper machine installed in  which was capable of making rolls of fine paper  inches wide this giant paper machine designed by glatfelter engineers and housed in a new building was the world’s first fourdrinier to have an easily replaceable wire belt perhaps reflecting these changes spring grove’s main street where the company’s office building was located was first paved in  in  just a year before the great stock market crash annual production at p h glatfelter company had reached  million pounds and the number of employees stood at  that year in keeping with the company’s policy of “maintaining a modern efficient mill” p h glatfelter ii william’s son introduced a new tenyear modernization program which included the installation of an even larger inch fourdrinier machine as a result the outlook for the company seemed especially bright but just two years later conditions noticeably changed for the worse by  the country was quickly falling into an economic crisis and sales at p h glatfelter company and other paper concerns were plummeting william glatfelter moreover unexpectedly died in april unlike many other firms p h glatfelter company managed to survive the depression of the s and its new president p h glatfelter ii was even able to complete his modernization program at a cost of some  million as part of this program one of the company’s pulp mills was refurbished and its capacity was doubled when the economy picked up again during world war ii p h glatfelter company added among other improvements new equipment for bleaching paper p h glatfelter ii president until january   guided the company through the postwar economic boom and started a new effort at reforestation and environmental stewardship in  the company set aside  acres of land near fairfield pennsylvania to create the state’s first tree farm between  and  it spent  million to build a wastewater treatment plant and a new ton boiler was installed in  to more efficiently burn a pulp byproduct called black liquor during this time there were also millions of dollars spent on capital improvements for increased production for example the company’s seventh and eighth paper machines were added in  and  respectively and between  and  capital expenditures alone were nearly  million an especially ambitious project was the p h glatfelter dam completed in  along a stretch of the codorus creek about five miles south of spring grove the dam created a billiongallon reservoir called lake marburg which was intended to guarantee a reliable water supply for the glatfelter mill farther downstream in addition the reservoir was eventually surrounded by a newly created acre codorus state park which included a public swimming pool and provided opportunities for camping hiking horseback riding and boating the project cost some  million split equally between p h glatfelter company and the pennsylvania bureau of state parks p h glatfelter ii retired in  and his son p h glatfelter iii became president a position he held for a decade an early challenge for the new president was hurricane agnes which hit the eastern seaboard in june of  and created severe floods in spring grove according to p h glatfelter iii the flood “caused more damage and financial loss to the company than any other single event” among other notable developments during his tenure was the  decision by glatfelter employees to join the united paperworkers international union and in  the company received the isaac walton league of america clean water award the company entered a new product line in  with its purchase of bergstrom paper company a leading manufacturer of recycled printing paper with mills in neenah wisconsin and west carrollton ohio the west carrollton mill was sold in  but during the s the company rebuilt all three paper machines at the neenah plant thomas c norris named president in  was the first person outside the glatfelter family to run the company his experience with p h glatfelter company stretched back to  when he took a parttime job in the paper mill at the age of  like his predecessors norris oversaw a program of new capital expenditures including the rebuilding of two paper machines at spring grove even more significant was the company’s  million purchase of ecusta corporation located in pisgah forest north carolina which made extremely thin flax paper for the tobacco industry the purchase of ecusta doubled the number of glatfelter employees from  to  and provided along with uncoated and recycled printing paper the third major underpinning of the company’s sales uncoated printing paper however remained its core product which by the early s made up some  percent of all paper used in the united states for hardcover trade books among the many wellknown books printed on glatfelter paper were norman mailer’s harlot’s ghost  steven king’s four past midnight  and alexandra ripley’s scarlett  the sequel to margaret mitchell’s gone with the wind which in  used glatfelter paper for the original printing great books of the western world a multivolume publication of classics was printed with recycled paper from the neenah mill p h glatfelter company headed into the s with an exceptionally strong financial base secured by its remarkable lack of debt although p h glatfelter company has occasionally borrowed money—for example  million in  to complete its acquisition of ecusta—even this loan was paid off in just two years the company’s strength was also found in its emphasis on specialized highquality paper which was much less affected by recurring business cycles than largevolume“commodity” paper products in  glatfelter’s chief financial officer m a johnson ii explained“our emphasis is on profit not on volume that’s why we continue to be a niche company one that is competing in areas where we’re not banging heads with people who are commodityoriented” since the mids the company has expressed considerable selfconfidence in its financial strength by its repurchase of millions of outstanding shares of glatfelter stock with its financial security and its emphasis on specialty products p h glatfelter company was able to weather profitably the declining market conditions for paper which beginning in  were spurred by industry overproduction glatfelter’s record sales of  million in   million in  and  million in  tumbled to  million and  million respectively in  and  even so the company still posted a respectable net profit of  million in  down from a high of  million in  the company’s good health was credited to its oldfashioned conservative business philosophy as well as to the able guidance of its president chief executive officer and chairman of the board thomas norris who in  was one of only eleven corporate leaders given financial world’s silver award for “superior business leadership and achievement” principal subsidiaries ecusta australia pty limited ecusta fibres ltd canada glatfelter pulp wood company further reading abelson reed “p h glatfelter co” fortune june   p  cauffielzinn jan “the p h glatfelter company” the barker inhouse magazine of p h glatfelter company spring pp – summer pp – fall pp – and winter pp –  cochran thomas n “p h glatfelter co” barren’s august   pp – henriques diana b “a paper company that loves itself” new york times december   p f lipper mark paper people progress the story of the p h glatfelter company of spring grove pennsylvania spring grove pennsylvania p h glatfelter company  morris kathleen and elicia brown “ ceo of the year silver award winners” financial world march   p  p h glatfelter company annual reports spring grove pennsylvania p h glatfelter company – “p h glatfelter co spring grove pa” –  years of papermaking in america stroudsburg pennsylvania lockwood trade journal co  p  —thomas riggs cite this article pick a style below and copy the text for your bibliography mla chicago apa p h glatfelter company international directory of company histories  encyclopediacom  jul  httpwwwencyclopediacom p h glatfelter company international directory of company histories  encyclopediacom july   httpwwwencyclopediacombookspoliticsandbusinessmagazinesphglatfeltercompany p h glatfelter company international directory of company histories  retrieved july   from encyclopediacom httpwwwencyclopediacombookspoliticsandbusinessmagazinesphglatfeltercompany learn more about citation styles p h glatfelter co nyseglt quotes  news  google financecookies help us deliver our services by using our services you agree to our use of cookieslearn moregot itmy accountsearchmapsyoutubeplaynewsgmaildrivecalendargoogletranslatephotosmoreshoppingwalletfinancedocsbooksbloggercontactshangoutskeepeven more from googlesign inhidden fieldssearch financeadobe flash player is required for interactive charts allowfinancep h glatfelter conysegltadd to portfoliocompanysummarynewsrelated companieshistorical pricesfinancialsmarketsnewsportfoliosstock screenergoogle domestic trendsrecent quotes  daysyou have no recent quoteschg   p h glatfelter co  public nyseglt   watch thi